===Etymology===
[[File:2012-01-17 13-20-51 Spain Canarias Ajuy.jpg|thumb|Spindrift ''(sense 1.1)'' off the [[coast#Noun|coast]] of [[Fuerteventura]], one of the [[Canary Islands]], [[Spain]].]]

A variant of {{m|en|spoondrift}} {{qualifier|archaic}}, apparently due to the pronunciation of this word in southwestern Scotland.<ref name="OED">{{R:OED Online|pos=n|id=186695|date=March 2022|nodot=1}}; {{R:Lexico|pos=n}}</ref> {{m|en||Spoondrift}} is derived from {{compound|en|spoon|drift|t2=mass of matter driven or forced onward together in a body, etc., especially by wind or water|nocat=1}}; {{m|en||spoon}} is a variant of {{m|en|spoom|t=to sail briskly with the wind astern, with or without sails hoisted}}.<ref>{{R:OED Online|entry=spoondrift|pos=n|id=187412|date=September 2019}}</ref>

The word was popularized in English from the late 19th century by its use in the novels of the Scottish-born author [[w:William Black (novelist)|William Black]] (1841–1898).<ref name="OED"/>

